commit ea7f8685455cfec105aa7f1c3d7659651fd8dd45
Author: Oskar Gerlicz Kowalczuk <oskar@gerlicz.space>

liveupdate: guard FLB counters against underflow

This commit guards FLB lifetime counters against underflow on unpreserve
and finish. It adds warnings and prevents decrementing when the counters
are already zero.

> diff --git a/kernel/liveupdate/luo_flb.c b/kernel/liveupdate/luo_flb.c
> index 3672cbf8e075..06501360fa3f 100644
> --- a/kernel/liveupdate/luo_flb.c
> +++ b/kernel/liveupdate/luo_flb.c
[ ... ]
> @@ -201,8 +204,12 @@ static void luo_flb_file_finish_one(struct liveupdate_flb *flb)
>  	struct luo_flb_private *private = luo_flb_get_private(flb);
>  	u64 count;
>  
> -	scoped_guard(mutex, &private->incoming.lock)
> +	scoped_guard(mutex, &private->incoming.lock) {
> +		if (WARN_ON_ONCE(!private->incoming.count))
> +			return;
> +
>  		count = --private->incoming.count;
> +	}
>  
>  	if (!count) {
>  		struct liveupdate_flb_op_args args = {0};

Could this introduce a regression where a time-of-check to time-of-use race
in liveupdate_flb_get_incoming() allows returning a NULL object pointer on
success?

If liveupdate_flb_get_incoming() performs a lockless check of
private->incoming.obj and it is initially non-NULL, it will skip calling
luo_flb_retrieve_one().

If a concurrent execution of luo_flb_file_finish_one() then decrements
count to zero, it will clear the object pointer:

CPU1
luo_flb_file_finish_one()
    scoped_guard(mutex, &private->incoming.lock) {
        ...
        private->incoming.obj = NULL;
        private->incoming.finished = true;
    }

CPU2 would then acquire the lock in liveupdate_flb_get_incoming(), but fail
to re-verify the state:

    if (!private->incoming.obj) {
        ...
    }

    guard(mutex)(&private->incoming.lock);
    *objp = private->incoming.obj;

    return 0;

Would CPU2 then return 0 with a NULL object pointer, causing a caller
checking for success to dereference a NULL pointer?

The API is designed to return -ENODATA if called after the FLB is finished,
but this race appears to bypass that protection.

